======================================================================
THE COMPLEMENTARY SIEVE THEOREM
======================================================================

THE DUALITY:

Tournament side (USES {2,3,5}):
  z² - 5z + 6 = (z-2)(z-3)
  Roots: 2 = KEY₁, 3 = KEY₂
  Sum: 5 = KEY₁ + KEY₂
  Product: 6 = KEY₁ · KEY₂
  h(E₈) = 2·3·5 = 30

Exponent side (AVOIDS {2,3,5}):
  Totatives of 30: integers in [1,30) coprime to 2, 3, and 5
  [1, 7, 11, 13, 17, 19, 23, 29]
  Count: φ(30) = 8 = rank(E₈)

Partition of [1, 30):
  Tournament-divisible: [2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 8, 9, 10, 12, 14, 15, 16, 18, 20, 21, 22, 24, 25, 26, 27, 28]
  Exponent-coprime:     [1, 7, 11, 13, 17, 19, 23, 29]
  Sizes: 21 + 8 = 29 = 29

Structure of each side:
  Tournament side: all multiples of 2, 3, or 5 in [2,30)
    = even numbers ∪ multiples of 3 ∪ multiples of 5
  Exponent side: [1, 7, 11, 13, 17, 19, 23, 29]
    = {1} ∪ {primes p : 5 < p < 30}

  Primes in (5, 30): [7, 11, 13, 17, 19, 23, 29]
  E₈ exponents \ {1}: [7, 11, 13, 17, 19, 23, 29]
  Match: ✓

======================================================================
PART 2: THE SIEVE EXTENDS TO ALL EXCEPTIONALS
======================================================================

G₂: h = 6, prime factors = [2, 3]
  Totatives of 6: [1, 5]
  Exponents:        [1, 5]
  Exponents = totatives? ✓
  rank = 2, φ(h) = 2, rank - φ(h) = 0

F₄: h = 12, prime factors = [2, 3]
  Totatives of 12: [1, 5, 7, 11]
  Exponents:        [1, 5, 7, 11]
  Exponents = totatives? ✓
  rank = 4, φ(h) = 4, rank - φ(h) = 0

E₆: h = 12, prime factors = [2, 3]
  Totatives of 12: [1, 5, 7, 11]
  Exponents:        [1, 4, 5, 7, 8, 11]
  Exponents = totatives? ✗
  Non-coprime exponents: [4, 8]
  Extra exponents (not totatives): [4, 8]
  Missing totatives: []
  rank = 6, φ(h) = 4, rank - φ(h) = 2

E₇: h = 18, prime factors = [2, 3]
  Totatives of 18: [1, 5, 7, 11, 13, 17]
  Exponents:        [1, 5, 7, 9, 11, 13, 17]
  Exponents = totatives? ✗
  Non-coprime exponents: [9]
  Extra exponents (not totatives): [9]
  Missing totatives: []
  rank = 7, φ(h) = 6, rank - φ(h) = 1

E₈: h = 30, prime factors = [2, 3, 5]
  Totatives of 30: [1, 7, 11, 13, 17, 19, 23, 29]
  Exponents:        [1, 7, 11, 13, 17, 19, 23, 29]
  Exponents = totatives? ✓
  rank = 8, φ(h) = 8, rank - φ(h) = 0

PATTERN:
  G₂, F₄, E₈: exponents = totatives (rank = φ(h))
  E₆: 2 extra exponents {4, 8} (rank = φ(h) + 2)
  E₇: 1 extra exponent {9} (rank = φ(h) + 1)

  The 'extra' exponents are those NOT coprime to h:
  E₆ extras: gcd(4,12)=4, gcd(8,12)=4 — both divide by KEY₁²
  E₇ extra:  gcd(9,18)=9 — divides by KEY₂²

  E₆ has det = 3 = KEY₂ and extra exponents at h/KEY₂ positions
  E₇ has det = 2 = KEY₁ and extra exponent at h/KEY₁ = 9

CENTER-EXPONENT CORRESPONDENCE:
  E₆: |Z| = det = 3, extra exponents = 2 = rank - φ(h)
  E₇: |Z| = det = 2, extra exponents = 1 = rank - φ(h)
  G₂, F₄, E₈: |Z| = det = 1, extra exponents = 0

  rank - φ(h) = #{non-coprime exponents}
  These are the exponents from the CENTER of the Lie algebra!

======================================================================
PART 3: WHAT THE SIEVE TELLS US ABOUT TOURNAMENTS
======================================================================

Tournament polynomial discriminant analysis:
  Δ = 5² - 4·6 = 25 - 24 = 1
  √Δ = 1
  Roots = (5 ± 1)/2 = 2 and 3

  The discriminant Δ = 1 is MINIMAL for integer-root quadratics!
  (Two distinct roots must differ by at least 1)

Minimal discriminant quadratics with positive integer roots:
  (z-1)(z-2): z² - 3z + 2, h=6, product abc = 6
  (z-2)(z-3): z² - 5z + 6, h=30, product abc = 30
  (z-3)(z-4): z² - 7z + 12, h=84, product abc = 84
  (z-4)(z-5): z² - 9z + 20, h=180, product abc = 180
  (z-5)(z-6): z² - 11z + 30, h=330, product abc = 330
  (z-6)(z-7): z² - 13z + 42, h=546, product abc = 546
  (z-7)(z-8): z² - 15z + 56, h=840, product abc = 840
  (z-8)(z-9): z² - 17z + 72, h=1224, product abc = 1224
  (z-9)(z-10): z² - 19z + 90, h=1710, product abc = 1710

WHY (2,3) IS SPECIAL:

  For consecutive roots (n, n+1):
  h = n·(n+1)·(2n+1) = product × sum

  n=1: (1,2,3), h=6, φ(h)=2
  n=2: (2,3,5), h=30, φ(h)=8
  n=3: (3,4,7), h=84, φ(h)=24
  n=4: (4,5,9), h=180, φ(h)=48
  n=5: (5,6,11), h=330, φ(h)=80
  n=6: (6,7,13), h=546, φ(h)=144
  n=7: (7,8,15), h=840, φ(h)=192

  n=2: (2,3,5), h=30, φ(30)=8 — THIS gives E₈!
  n=1: (1,2,3), h=6,  φ(6)=2  — THIS gives G₂!

THE HIERARCHY OF CONSECUTIVE TRIPLES:
  G₂:  (1, 2, 3) — the simplest triple
  E₈:  (2, 3, 5) — the tournament prime triple
  ???:  (3, 4, 7) — h = 84, φ(84) = 24
  ???:  (4, 5, 9) — h = 180, φ(180) = 48

Hyperbolic constraint 1/a + 1/b > 1/2:
  (1,2): 1/1+1/2 = 1.500000  > 1/2 → exceptional possible
  (2,3): 1/2+1/3 = 0.833333  > 1/2 → exceptional possible
  (3,4): 1/3+1/4 = 0.583333  > 1/2 → exceptional possible
  (4,5): 1/4+1/5 = 0.450000  ≤ 1/2 → NO exceptional
  (5,6): 1/5+1/6 = 0.366667  ≤ 1/2 → NO exceptional
  (6,7): 1/6+1/7 = 0.309524  ≤ 1/2 → NO exceptional
  (7,8): 1/7+1/8 = 0.267857  ≤ 1/2 → NO exceptional

THE ADE CONSTRAINT: 1/p + 1/q + 1/r > 1
  This is equivalent to: (p,q,r) = (2,3,5) is the LAST triple
  Beyond E₈, the excess becomes 0 or negative
  E₈ lives at the BOUNDARY of the classification

======================================================================
PART 4: THE COMPLEMENTARY SIEVE AS INFORMATION THEORY
======================================================================

Information-theoretic view:

  Channel width: [1, 30) = 29 symbols
  Tournament symbols (÷ by 2,3,5): 21
  Exponent symbols (coprime to 30):  8
  Ratio: 21/29 : 8/29 = 0.7241 : 0.2759

  Binary entropy of the partition:
  H = -21/29·log₂(21/29) - 8/29·log₂(8/29)
    = 0.849751 bits
    (max = 1 for even split)

Totient ratio φ(h)/h for products of first k primes:
  h =            2: φ(h)/h = 1/2 = 0.50000000  = Π(1-1/p) = 0.50000000
  h =            6: φ(h)/h = 2/6 = 0.33333333  = Π(1-1/p) = 0.33333333
  h =           30: φ(h)/h = 8/30 = 0.26666667  = Π(1-1/p) = 0.26666667
  h =          210: φ(h)/h = 48/210 = 0.22857143  = Π(1-1/p) = 0.22857143
  h =         2310: φ(h)/h = 480/2310 = 0.20779221  = Π(1-1/p) = 0.20779221
  h =        30030: φ(h)/h = 5760/30030 = 0.19180819  = Π(1-1/p) = 0.19180819
  h =       510510: φ(h)/h = 92160/510510 = 0.18052536  = Π(1-1/p) = 0.18052536
  h =      9699690: φ(h)/h = 1658880/9699690 = 0.17102402  = Π(1-1/p) = 0.17102402
  h =    223092870: φ(h)/h = 36495360/223092870 = 0.16358820  = Π(1-1/p) = 0.16358820
  h =   6469693230: φ(h)/h = 1021870080/6469693230 = 0.15794722  = Π(1-1/p) = 0.15794722

  The ratio → 0 (by Mertens' theorem)
  So the 'exponent side' gets THINNER as h grows
  E₈ is the last exceptional because beyond h=30,
  the exponent side would need MORE primes than available

======================================================================
PART 5: THE RECURRENCE VIEW OF THE SIEVE
======================================================================

E₈ exponents as eigenangle ratios m/h:
  m= 1: m/h =  1/30, λ = 4sin²(1π/30) = 0.043705
  m= 7: m/h =  7/30, λ = 4sin²(7π/30) = 1.790943
  m=11: m/h = 11/30, λ = 4sin²(11π/30) = 3.338261
  m=13: m/h = 13/30, λ = 4sin²(13π/30) = 3.827091
  m=17: m/h = 17/30, λ = 4sin²(17π/30) = 3.827091
  m=19: m/h = 19/30, λ = 4sin²(19π/30) = 3.338261
  m=23: m/h = 23/30, λ = 4sin²(23π/30) = 1.790943
  m=29: m/h = 29/30, λ = 4sin²(29π/30) = 0.043705

Eigenvalue pairs (self-dual under m ↔ h-m):
  ( 1, 29): λ = 0.043705
  ( 7, 23): λ = 1.790943
  (11, 19): λ = 3.338261
  (13, 17): λ = 3.827091

Chebyshev connection:
  Cartan eigenvalues = 2 - 2cos(2πm/h)
  These are the NODE VALUES of Chebyshev polynomials at 2πm/h
  Chebyshev recurrence: U_{n+1} = 2x·U_n - U_{n-1}
  This is a SECOND-ORDER LINEAR RECURRENCE — same structure as
  the tournament recurrence a(n) = 5a(n-1) - 6a(n-2)!

  Tournament recurrence: coefficient = 5 = KEY₁ + KEY₂, 6 = KEY₁ · KEY₂
  Chebyshev recurrence:  coefficient = 2x (variable), 1 (unit)
  At x = KEY₁+KEY₂/2 = 5/2, Chebyshev BECOMES the tournament recurrence!

Chebyshev U_n(5/2) vs tournament recurrence:
  Chebyshev:   [1, 5, 24, 115, 551, 2640, 12649, 60605]
  Tournament:  [1, 5, 19, 65, 211, 665, 2059, 6305]

======================================================================
PART 6: THE TRINITY — THREE VIEWS OF (2,3,5)
======================================================================

VIEW 1: ARITHMETIC (Number Theory)
  2 and 3 are the smallest primes
  5 = 2+3 is the next prime
  30 = 2·3·5 = primorial(5)
  φ(30) = 8 = 2³
  The sieve of [1,30) by {2,3,5} leaves 8 totatives

VIEW 2: GEOMETRY (Platonic Solids / ADE)
  (2,3,3) → Tetrahedron → E₆
  (2,3,4) → Cube/Octahedron → E₇
  (2,3,5) → Dodecahedron/Icosahedron → E₈
  1/2+1/3+1/5-1 = 1/30 = 1/h(E₈)
  The excess decreasing to 0 marks the end of classification

VIEW 3: DYNAMICS (Recurrences)
  2 = k-nacci attractor (weight 1)
  3 = k-nacci attractor (weight 2)
  5 = 2+3 = trace of the recurrence
  6 = 2·3 = determinant of the recurrence
  The recurrence z²-5z+6 = 0 bifurcates between 2 and 3

THE UNIFICATION:
  These three views are ASPECTS of a single structure:
  the COMPLEMENTARY SIEVE of integers by {2, 3, 5}.

  Tournament theory = the sieved-OUT part (divisible by 2,3,5)
  Lie exponent theory = the sieved-IN part (coprime to 2,3,5)

  Neither theory is complete without the other.
  Together they account for ALL integers.

