======================================================================
PART 8: FINAL SYNTHESIS — THE (2,3,5) CODE
======================================================================

THE (2,3,5) CODE — A SUMMARY OF ALL SESSION DISCOVERIES

LEVEL 0: The Atoms
  2 (KEY₁) and 3 (KEY₂) are the tournament polynomial roots
  They generate everything via z² - 5z + 6 = 0

LEVEL 1: The Triple
  5 = 2+3: third tournament prime, sum of roots
  Together: (2,3,5) = the atomic triple
  h(E₈) = 2·3·5 = 30 (their product)

LEVEL 2: The Sieve
  Tournament theory uses multiples of {2,3,5}
  Lie exponents avoid multiples of {2,3,5}
  E₈ rank = φ(30) = 8 = number of survivors

LEVEL 3: The Cascade
  2^k + 3 generates universal E-exponents:
    k=2: 7, k=3: 11 (shared by all E-types)
    k=4: 19 = h(E₇)+1 (E₈ only)
  Exponent gaps are palindromic over {2,4,6}

LEVEL 4: The Connections
  3-cycle formula: n(n²-1)/24
    At n=9: gives 30 = h(E₈)
    24 = |BT| connects to E₆
    9 = KEY₂² = CS boundary connects to E₇
    720 = 6! = |S₆| and T(6)=56=dim(V_E₇)

LEVEL 5: The Termination
  1/2+1/3+1/5 = 31/30 > 1 → E₈ exists
  1/2+1/3+1/7 = 41/42 < 1 → no E₉
  E₈ is the LAST exceptional because (2,3,5) is the
  last triple satisfying the hyperbolic excess constraint

THE ONE-LINE SUMMARY:
  All of Lie theory's exceptional structure is encoded in the
  complementary sieve of integers by the tournament primes {2,3,5}.
